{{Short description|Concept in sociology and political studies}} {{For|diversity outside of sociology and political science|Diversity (disambiguation){{!}}Diversity}} {{multiple issues| {{Cleanup|date=March 2012}} {{one source|date=October 2013}} {{Original research|date=August 2017}} }} {{Discrimination sidebar|Related}} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2024}} '''Diversity''' within groups is a key concept in [[sociology]] and [[political science]] that refers to the degree of difference along socially significant identifying features among the members of a purposefully defined group, such as any group differences in [[Race (human categorization)|racial]] or [[Ethnicity|ethnic classifications]], [[Ageing|age]], [[gender]], [[religion]], [[philosophy]], [[politics]], [[cultural diversity|culture]], [[Language#Linguistic diversity|language]], [[Disability|physical abilities]], [[Socioeconomics|socioeconomic background]], [[sexual orientation]], [[gender identity]], [[intelligence]], [[Health|physical health]], [[mental health]], [[Genetics|genetic attributes]], [[personality]], [[behavior]], or [[Physical attractiveness|attractiveness]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qcc.cuny.edu/|title=Queensborough Community College|website=www.qcc.cuny.edu|language=en|access-date=27 April 2019}}</ref>
When measuring human diversity, a [[diversity index]] exemplifies the likelihood that two randomly selected residents have different ethnicities. If all residents are of the same ethnic group it is zero by definition. If half are from one group and half from another, it is 50. The diversity index does not take into account the willingness of individuals to cooperate with those of other ethnicities.<ref>[http://projects.latimes.com/mapping-la/neighborhoods/diversity/neighborhood/list/ "Mapping L.A..," ''Los Angeles Times'' website]</ref>
==International human rights== {{Further|Inclusion (disability rights)}} The [[Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities]] affirms to "respect difference and acceptance of persons with disabilities as human diversity and [[human nature|humanity]]" for protection of human rights of persons with disabilities.<ref>[https://www.ohchr.org/en/instruments-mechanisms/instruments/convention-rights-persons-disabilities Article 3.d Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities, UN]</ref>
==Ideology== {{Main|Diversity ideologies|New Left|Multiculturalism}} Political [[creed]]s which support the idea that diversity is valuable and desirable hold that recognizing and promoting these{{Which|date=December 2021}} diverse cultures may aid [[communication]] between people of different backgrounds and lifestyles, leading to greater knowledge, understanding, and peaceful coexistence.{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} For example, "Respect for Diversity" is one of the six principles of the [[Global Greens Charter]], a [[manifesto]] subscribed to by [[Green party|green parties]] from all over the world. In contrast to diversity, some political creeds promote [[cultural assimilation]] as the process to lead to these ends.
